df2b = data.copy() # copy the data 
retweets = sum([tweet[:4] == 'RT @' for tweet in df2b['Tweet Text']]) # get the number of retweets

sizes = [retweets, originals] # set the porportions

plt.title("Original Content compared to Retweeted Content") # add a title 
plt.show() # plot the visualization

Coding Commentary for 2b:¶

I went with a pie chart because a bar chart with two bars makes it hard to see composition, which is what this visual is trying to demonstrate. A simple, fairly standard implementation of a pie chart is used. While a pie chart is not my favorite visual, it is useful to see composition and when paired with a label (such as this case), it can get the point across.

I enjoyed using a list comprehension then calling the sum on it. The list comprehension creates a list of booleans that can then be summed to represent the number of tweets that are retweets. Another interesting way to have done this would have been using regular expressions, however, when the format for all retweets is the same and they are going to be in the smame position literal positioning worked well too.

Observations for 2b:¶

df2h = data.copy() # data copy for this question

# couple of imports
import nltk
import string
# May need this if not already installed
nltk.download('stopwords')
nltk.download('punkt')


# function for doc conversion
def convert_doc_string_to_terms(doc):
    # prep doc
    stemmer = nltk.stem.porter.PorterStemmer() # instantiate the stemmer 
    fixed = doc.lower().translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation)) # clean up the string
    
    # do the steps
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(fixed) # generate the tokens
    noStops = [word for word in tokens if (not word in nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')) and (word != 'rt')] # remove stop words with list comprehension
    stemmed = [stemmer.stem(word) for word in noStops] # stem the words using list comprehension
    return stemmed # return the completed list of words

results = [ convert_doc_string_to_terms(doc) for doc in df2h['Tweet Text']] # run the conversion on all tweet words
tc = nltk.TextCollection(results) # creates text collection
fdist = tc.vocab() # creates the frequency distribution

unique_terms = list(fdist.keys()) # generates a list of unique terms
num_terms = len(unique_terms) # generates the number of unique terms 
print('\nUnique terms:', num_terms) # some output to demonstrate success
print('\nThe 50 Most common terms (automatically sorted):') # output to show top 50 terms
print(fdist.most_common(50)) # top 50 terms 
out = fdist.most_common(50) # stores the top 50 terms
plt.figure(figsize=(20,6)) # sets a fig size 
plt.title("50 Most Common Words in Tweets (using NLTK and Stemming)") # sets a title
plt.bar(range(len(out)), [val[1] for val in out], align='center') # uses list comprehension inline to generate the plot
plt.xticks(range(len(out)), [val[0] for val in out]) # generates the xticks using list comprehension
plt.xticks(rotation=90) # allows for easy reading 
plt.xlabel('Common Words in Tweets') # sets the x label
plt.ylabel('Number of Tweets') # sets the y label
plt.show() # shows the plot

out = fdist.most_common(50)[1:] # stores the top 49 terms
plt.figure(figsize=(20,6)) # sets a fig size 
plt.title("50 Most Common Words in Tweets (using NLTK and Stemming)\n(without enviro)") # sets a title
plt.bar(range(len(out)), [val[1] for val in out], align='center') # uses list comprehension inline to generate the plot
plt.xticks(range(len(out)), [val[0] for val in out]) # generates the xticks using list comprehension
plt.xticks(rotation=90) # allows for easy reading 
plt.xlabel('Common Words in Tweets') # sets the x label
plt.ylabel('Number of Tweets') # sets the y label
plt.show() # shows the plot

df2hii = data.copy() # copies the data 
allTopics = [] # storage list 
for tweet in df2hii['Tweet Text']: # loop through the tweets
  for i in tweet.split(): # split the tweet up 
    if i.startswith("#"): # checks if hashtag
      i = re.sub('[\W_]+', '', i).lower() # removes and lowers all non alpha-numeric chars
      i = '#' + i 
      allTopics.append(i) # throw into an array 

topics = {} # storage dict
for topic in allTopics: # iterate over list 
  if topic not in topics.keys(): # check if in dict
    topics[topic] = 1 # instantiate key-value pair in dict if not present
  else:  # increment up if already in dict
    topics[topic] += 1 # increment the value if already in dict 
    
topics = dict(sorted(topics.items(), key = itemgetter(1), reverse = True)[:20]) # sort dict for plotting
keys = topics.keys() # get x values
values = topics.values() # get y values
plt.figure(figsize = (20,6)) # set figsize 
plt.title("50 Most Common Words in Tweets (using NLTK and Stemming)\n (with #enviroed)") # set title
plt.xticks(rotation=45) # set rotation for easy viewing
plt.xlabel('Topic') # set x label
plt.ylabel('Number of Tweets') # set y label
plt.bar(keys, values) # generate the plot
plt.show() # show the plot

topics = dict(sorted(topics.items(), key = itemgetter(1), reverse = True)[1:20]) # sort dict and ignore the first

2 i: Who is tweeting?¶

2 i.i: Create a directed, weighted, social network graph where the nodes are the unique twitter users, the edges indicate if a user has mentioned another user in a tweet, and the weights are a count of how many times the user was mentioned. (Note that edges should be directed from the mentioning user to the mentioned user.) [The day 17 tutorial may be helpful here.]¶

In [16]:
df2i = data.copy() # create a copy


G = nx.DiGraph() # start the directed graph
G.add_nodes_from(df2i['Screen Name'].unique()) # add the nodes


mentions =  re.compile(r'\s+\@\w+[^:!.%,]') # id usernames in tweet text regex 
mentions = [mentions.findall(tweet) for tweet in df2i['Tweet Text']] # id usernames in tweet text to list 

edges = {} # storage dict 
for tweet, mention in zip(df2i['Screen Name'],mentions): # zips together screen name and mentions
  for m in mention: # gets individual mention within a tweet
    if m not in df2i['Screen Name']: # passes over usernames that don't exist 
      pass
    edge = tuple([tweet] + [m]) # creates the edge
    if edge not in edges.keys(): # checks if edge already exists 
      edges[edge] = 1 # initializes the key value pair 
    else: # updates the key value pair if its already in the dict 
      edges[edge] += 1

weighted_edges = [tuple(list(k) + [v]) for k, v in edges.items()] # cleans up the weighted edges 
print(len(weighted_edges)) # some quick checking
print(weighted_edges[:5]) # some quick checking 

G.add_weighted_edges_from(weighted_edges) # add a tuple of three things as edges to graph

eigenvector_dict = nx.eigenvector_centrality(G) # Run eigenvector centrality
nx.set_node_attributes(G, eigenvector_dict, 'eigenvector')  # update node attributes

import requests # used to open the urls within tweets
from tldextract import extract # extractor 
df2ki = data.copy() # copies the data 
xpt = 0 # an exceptions counter

allLinks = [] # all links storage list
urls = [] # all urls storage list for cleaned urls 
for tweet in df2ki['Tweet Text']: # iterates over tweet text 
    allLinks.append(re.findall(r'(https?://\S+)', tweet)) # finds all the links 

for item in allLinks: # iterates all the links that were found 
    if len(item) == 0: # checks for null links 
        allLinks.remove(item) # removes null links 
    for url in item: # continues with iteration
        if url[-1:] != '': # cleans out the crappy char 
            urls.append(url) # appends it to the clean url list 
c = 0 # record counter
realUrls = [] # creates a list for the actual URLS from twitter urls 

# this opens each of the twitter urls 
for url in urls: # iterates over each url
  try: # tries it and catches exceptions 
    realUrl = requests.get(url, allow_redirects = True, timeout=4).url # opens and retrieves real url
#    print('twitter url:', url, 'real url:', realUrl, 'url', c, ' of', len(urls)) # prints out for debugging 
    tsd, td, tsu = extract(realUrl) # prints abc, hostname, com
    r_url = td + '.' + tsu # will prints as hostname.com
    realUrls.append(r_url) # gets the right one and stores it
  except: # catches exceptions 
    xpt += 1 # increments the number of exceptions to keep track
#    print("An exception occurred on URL ", url, " total errors now", xpt, " of", c, "records") # a debug statement to check if it works 
  c += 1 # incremements the counter to keep track

import cartopy.crs as ccrs # the specific matplotlib extension
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt # reimplementing mpl

locs = {} # a storage dict 
for l, ln in zip(lat,lng): # zips together two lists of lat and long
    loc = tuple([l] + [ln]) # creates a tuple 
    if loc not in locs.keys(): # checks if edge already exists 
      locs[loc] = 1 # initializes the key value pair 
    else: # updates the key value pair if its already in the dict 
      locs[loc] += 1 # increments up 

latitude, longitude = [list(c) for c in zip(*locs)] # seperates out the keyvalue pair into distict lists
density = locs.values() # seperates the values into their own list
datum = tuple(zip(latitude,longitude,density)) # creates a tuple of each one to zip together for pandas df
datum = pd.DataFrame(datum,columns = ['lat', 'long','density']) # creates a pandas df to play well with mpl
lat = datum.lat # creating series for latitude
lng = datum.long # creating series for longitude
dens = datum.density # creating series for density
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (10,10)) # setting the fig size

2k.ii Code Commentary:¶

I used two cells to complete this challenge. The first sets all the data up and the second one counts it up and displays it. There are three main challenges here: transforming the data from strings to latitude and longitudes, getting the tweet density per location, and then displaying it on a map.

The data is transformed using geocoder to make API calls to google to get the latitudes and longitudes. Once I learned how to use the API key and turn off the limits on the API calls, this step was a breeze. I used the dictionary methods using tuples to count the number of times a particular coordinate was in there and stored it as key value pairs as done many times throughout this homework. I then unzipped and massaged these into a data frame to play nicely with matplotlib.
